3
00:01:18,858 --> 00:01:22,019
<i>1926. Macon, Georgia

4
00:01:23,019 --> 00:01:27,641
The only thing I ever
knew was cotton.

5
00:01:28,978 --> 00:01:31,972
It was hard work.

6
00:01:35,380 --> 00:01:39,663
...and you know the cotton is
ready when the bulb splits,

7
00:01:39,924 --> 00:01:43,470
and the bulb is star shaped,
like a big old star

8
00:01:43,612 --> 00:01:49,018
in the sky. Like your big ol'
head. Oh, that's some kind!

9
00:01:52,672 --> 00:01:56,379
But I didn't mind because I got to
spend all day with my dad.

10
00:01:56,523 --> 00:01:59,073
Hurry up and take this picture.
- Take a picture of you?

11
00:01:59,410 --> 00:02:02,034
Why don't everybody smile?

12
00:02:11,494 --> 00:02:14,909
Hattie, come on. I need
your help in the shed.

13
00:02:15,896 --> 00:02:17,344
Come on.

14
00:02:26,745 --> 00:02:29,625
Pa, where is he taking ma?
- Get back to work!

15
00:02:31,669 --> 00:02:33,871
Cecil, get back to work!

16
00:02:35,497 --> 00:02:37,920
Mamma! - Come here.

17
00:02:38,835 --> 00:02:43,129
Look at me boy. Don't lose
your temper with that man.

18
00:02:43,224 --> 00:02:47,528
This is his world. We just
living in it. You hear me?

19
00:02:47,537 --> 00:02:49,957
Now get on back to work!

20
00:03:21,147 --> 00:03:23,414
Pa, what you gonna do?

21
00:03:28,176 --> 00:03:30,090
Hey!

22
00:03:44,726 --> 00:03:46,052
Dad!

23
00:04:02,023 --> 00:04:04,744
What are you looking at?! Huh?

24
00:04:04,902 --> 00:04:08,076
Who wants to go next?
You get back to work!

25
00:04:15,818 --> 00:04:21,229
Hey you, get some of the hands to
help dig a hole for his pa. Hurry up!

26
00:04:28,977 --> 00:04:32,418
Stop crying.

27
00:04:33,515 --> 00:04:36,448
I'm gonna have you
in the house now.

28
00:04:40,466 --> 00:04:44,897
I'm gonna teach you how
to be a house nigger.

29
00:04:51,456 --> 00:04:53,833
INSPIRED BY THE TRUE STORY

30
00:04:55,078 --> 00:04:59,448
He's commin'. - Yes, sir.
- And quiet when you're serving.

31
00:04:59,634 --> 00:05:03,140
I don't even want to hear
you breathe. - Yes, ma'am.

32
00:05:12,619 --> 00:05:17,443
It was much nicer working in the
house than in the field.

33
00:05:17,792 --> 00:05:21,134
Crazy, make it from the left.

34
00:05:26,344 --> 00:05:28,350
Give me more.

35
00:05:57,056 --> 00:06:02,431
When I got older, I knew I had to
go before he killed me too.

36
00:06:07,603 --> 00:06:10,069
Part of me was scared to leave,

37
00:06:10,471 --> 00:06:13,198
it was the only world I ever knew.

38
00:06:22,674 --> 00:06:25,074
Ma, I took pa's watch.

39
00:06:31,475 --> 00:06:34,239
Ma?

40
00:06:35,192 --> 00:06:37,665
Ma, I'm leavin'.

41
00:06:39,321 --> 00:06:42,666
My mamma never spoke much after that.

42
00:06:43,245 --> 00:06:47,030
I knew she'd miss me.
But I also knew

43
00:06:47,130 --> 00:06:50,456
she wanted me to leave that place.

44
00:06:58,046 --> 00:07:01,334
And even though
Miss Annabeth never said it,

45
00:07:01,890 --> 00:07:04,135
I knew she'd miss me too.

46
00:07:17,903 --> 00:07:22,331
I don't think God meant for people
to not have a family.

47
00:07:29,821 --> 00:07:34,429
Outside the cotton fields was even
worse than I thought it'd be.

48
00:07:36,013 --> 00:07:40,655
No one would give me a job, or
food, or a place to sleep.

49
00:07:49,092 --> 00:07:52,000
Any white man could kill
any of us at any time...

50
00:07:52,105 --> 00:07:54,376
and not be punished for it.

51
00:07:55,363 --> 00:07:58,923
The law wasn't on our side.

52
00:08:01,090 --> 00:08:04,456
The law was against us.

53
00:08:10,568 --> 00:08:13,399
I was hungry all the time.

54
00:08:41,782 --> 00:08:44,290
You know what could
happen to you, son?

55
00:08:48,958 --> 00:08:51,080
Get up.

56
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,314
I said get up.

57
00:09:02,545 --> 00:09:07,085
I'm going to have to lie to the
boss man about that window.

58
00:09:07,505 --> 00:09:11,473
Good Lord says you
ain't supposed to lie.

59
00:09:11,815 --> 00:09:13,418
Sorry sir.

60
00:09:14,854 --> 00:09:16,663
Where's your ma and your pa?

61
00:09:17,400 --> 00:09:20,927
My Ma crazy in the head
and my Pa got killed.

62
00:09:24,560 --> 00:09:26,786
I'ma make you some ham sandwiches

63
00:09:27,052 --> 00:09:28,948
and send you on your way.

64
00:09:29,486 --> 00:09:34,639
The boss will be here any minute.
Sunday's our busiest morning.

65
00:09:35,804 --> 00:09:39,306
You looking for some help?
I know how to serve.

66
00:09:40,565 --> 00:09:44,095
You done broke our window.
You done stole our food.

67
00:09:44,105 --> 00:09:47,681
And now you asking for a job?
- Back in Macon, I'ma house nigger.

68
00:09:47,781 --> 00:09:48,933
A good one.

69
00:09:52,096 --> 00:09:55,263
Don't you ever use that word son.

70
00:09:55,438 --> 00:09:59,767
That's the white man's word.
It's filled with hate.

71
00:10:00,478 --> 00:10:03,380
Didn't your father
teach you any better?

72
00:10:08,320 --> 00:10:10,453
Slow down! - Yes, sir.

73
00:10:11,710 --> 00:10:14,203
You gotta look 'em in their eyes.

74
00:10:15,005 --> 00:10:20,465
See what it is they want, got it?
- Sure, Mr Maynard, I got it!

75
00:10:26,232 --> 00:10:29,678
See what it is they need...

76
00:10:30,840 --> 00:10:32,840
Right this way.

77
00:10:33,564 --> 00:10:35,237
Anticipate.

78
00:10:44,787 --> 00:10:46,580
I'm - I'm sorry ma'am.

79
00:10:49,161 --> 00:10:53,358
When you smile with
the eyes, be principle.

80
00:11:01,069 --> 00:11:02,941
Perfect!

81
00:11:06,794 --> 00:11:09,800
Don't forget to save me chitlins.
- Why do you like chitlins so much?

82
00:11:09,861 --> 00:11:14,865
Cuz, it's good eating. The manager
of the Excelsior in DC,

83
00:11:15,508 --> 00:11:20,158
he came by yesterday.
He offered me a job as a butler.

84
00:11:20,209 --> 00:11:22,641
They must be paying you
top dollar, huh boss?

85
00:11:24,411 --> 00:11:28,498
Yeah...I was thinking
about taking it.

86
00:11:29,003 --> 00:11:32,678
But I dunno, I'm too old to
be leaving North Carolina.

87
00:11:33,155 --> 00:11:35,903
I'm just fine right here.

88
00:11:37,085 --> 00:11:40,156
I told them to hire you.

89
00:11:40,322 --> 00:11:42,610
I'm just now finding my
way 'round this hotel.

90
00:11:43,031 --> 00:11:45,340
I'm not ready for those
high falootin' white people

91
00:11:45,440 --> 00:11:48,934
with all their fancy words.
- Cecil, we got two faces.

92
00:11:49,846 --> 00:11:53,937
Ours, and the ones that we
got to show the white folks.

93
00:11:54,700 --> 00:11:57,201
Now to get up in the world,

94
00:11:57,262 --> 00:12:00,744
you have to make them feel
nonthreatened.

95
00:12:02,081 --> 00:12:05,575
Use that all fancy
words that I taught you.

96
00:12:08,200 --> 00:12:12,988
White folks up north, they
like some uppity coloreds.

97
00:12:15,010 --> 00:12:16,952
Yeah.

98
00:12:17,293 --> 00:12:18,795
<i>1957. Washington, DC

99
00:12:18,895 --> 00:12:22,722
When I took that job up in
Washington, DC,

100
00:12:22,823 --> 00:12:26,975
it was the most beautiful
hotel I had ever seen.

101
00:12:33,429 --> 00:12:36,792
I hope I wasn't too
presumptuous to have prepared

102
00:12:36,803 --> 00:12:40,156
a few spirits after your
long journey in from Buffalo.

103
00:12:42,177 --> 00:12:46,107
Best decision that court ever made
was to slow this whole mess down.

104
00:12:46,157 --> 00:12:49,749
Nigger boys in school with white girls?!
Who ever heard of such a thing?

105
00:12:50,601 --> 00:12:53,063
Next thing you know
they'd be fornicatin'.

106
00:12:54,042 --> 00:12:57,932
Gentlemen, this is different.
We could start another Civil War.

107
00:12:59,457 --> 00:13:03,495
Cecil, what do you think about niggers
going to school with white children?

108
00:13:04,504 --> 00:13:06,437
To be honest with you, Mr. Jenkins,

109
00:13:06,958 --> 00:13:12,625
I tend to not to be too concerned
with American or European politics.

110
00:13:12,655 --> 00:13:16,253
Nor should you, Cecil,
they're all criminals.

111
00:13:16,274 --> 00:13:18,797
Earl Warren should be
shot and hanged.

112
00:13:19,105 --> 00:13:23,461
That dumb son of bitch judge
is trying to integrate our schools.

113
00:13:23,481 --> 00:13:28,940
I think, judge Warren is going to
find that quite a challenge.

114
00:13:29,203 --> 00:13:32,041
Damn right, Cecil! Damn right!

115
00:13:32,074 --> 00:13:37,225
Never in my life did I dream that I would
work in a place as fancy as this.

116
00:13:38,940 --> 00:13:41,562
I never dreamed
my life could be so good.

117
00:13:50,677 --> 00:13:53,554
Gloria and I met
working at the Excelsior.

118
00:13:54,309 --> 00:13:57,196
She was a maid at the
hotel. But now,

119
00:13:57,207 --> 00:14:00,051
her only job was
raising our two boys.

120
00:14:03,206 --> 00:14:06,724
I made sure that they never
laid eyes on a cotton field.

121
00:14:09,306 --> 00:14:10,817
I gotta pee.

122
00:14:11,418 --> 00:14:14,870
Not today. Don't try that.
Finish that homework.

123
00:14:15,179 --> 00:14:17,878
Where's Louis at?
- He's taking the trash out.

124
00:14:17,927 --> 00:14:20,574
Working late again, huh?
How was your shift?

125
00:14:20,687 --> 00:14:22,904
Beats working for a livin'.

126
00:14:23,637 --> 00:14:25,856
I miss you at night, honey.

127
00:14:29,708 --> 00:14:32,592
Didn't you say you gotta pee?
Go ahead then.

128
00:14:32,713 --> 00:14:35,270
Wash your hands when you come
out of that bathroom, boy.

129
00:14:37,606 --> 00:14:40,846
Good morning.
- Good morning, sir.

130
00:14:46,105 --> 00:14:51,251
Hey dad! - Hey Louis.
You alright? - Yeah, I'm fine.

131
00:14:52,544 --> 00:14:55,227
That woman whose son got killed,

132
00:14:55,394 --> 00:14:58,853
she's around doing speeches now.
What's her name, honey?

133
00:14:59,705 --> 00:15:02,447
Mamie Till. - Mamie Till...

134
00:15:04,715 --> 00:15:06,780
I remember that story
just like it was yesterday

135
00:15:06,800 --> 00:15:09,598
even though it was three years ago.

136
00:15:10,104 --> 00:15:12,849
It was dis-damn-graceful
what they did to that boy

137
00:15:13,277 --> 00:15:15,637
just for looking at a white woman...

138
00:15:16,030 --> 00:15:19,641
Beat him up,
threw his body in the river...

139
00:15:20,762 --> 00:15:24,713
Killed him. He was just 14
at the time.

140
00:15:25,204 --> 00:15:27,002
Crazy white folks down south.

141
00:15:27,042 --> 00:15:30,279
Thanks, ma. - At least we have
it a little better here in DC, huh?

142
00:15:30,380 --> 00:15:34,070
Still treating us bad too.
- Get on down here Charlie!

143
00:15:34,319 --> 00:15:37,346
Wash your hands. - Louis said we
should stop taking the white man's shit.

144
00:15:37,701 --> 00:15:39,774
Watch your mouth.
- Watch your mouth.

145
00:15:41,937 --> 00:15:44,143
Hello, Gaines' residence.

146
00:15:44,959 --> 00:15:48,900
Uh, yeah... Hold on Mr. Kidgan.
It's the boss man dad.

147
00:15:49,506 --> 00:15:51,459
What's he calling for?

148
00:15:51,500 --> 00:15:55,581
When the white man called,
I always assumed the worst.

149
00:15:56,401 --> 00:15:59,081
Yes sir? - I would have
put money on it,

150
00:15:59,112 --> 00:16:02,526
that I was getting laid off
or something that day.

151
00:16:29,490 --> 00:16:32,390
Would you follow me, please?
- Yes, sir.

152
00:16:40,200 --> 00:16:45,321
I'm Cecil Gaines. It's a pleasure to
meet you. - You as well. Have a seat.

153
00:17:00,341 --> 00:17:02,938
Are you political, Mr. Gaines?
- No, sir.

154
00:17:03,132 --> 00:17:08,477
Good, we have no tolerance for
politics at the White House.

155
00:17:10,237 --> 00:17:12,508
How did you find me?
- I didn't.

156
00:17:12,580 --> 00:17:15,247
You served RD Warner at
the Excelsior Hotel.

157
00:17:15,570 --> 00:17:18,107
He oversees operations
for the entire White House.

158
00:17:18,158 --> 00:17:21,108
You made quite an impression.
- I don't recall.

159
00:17:21,228 --> 00:17:24,453
Mr. Warner and myself make note
of potential staff around town.

160
00:17:25,822 --> 00:17:30,015
Butler positions rarely open as
most stay on for 30 years or more.

161
00:17:30,100 --> 00:17:32,527
I know I was quite surprised
when I got the call.

162
00:17:37,755 --> 00:17:40,027
It was a surprise for me as well.

163
00:17:40,457 --> 00:17:44,453
As the White House Maitre D',
I normally hire the butlers.

164
00:17:46,870 --> 00:17:49,701
Forgive me for saying this,
Mr. Fallows,

165
00:17:49,702 --> 00:17:51,585
I certainly wouldn't
want to be hired

166
00:17:51,605 --> 00:17:55,778
under circumstances that would
make you feel uncomfortable.

167
00:17:56,663 --> 00:18:00,552
Oh, really? - You need butlers
that you've hand picked,

168
00:18:00,660 --> 00:18:03,580
men to your liking that
will fulfill your vision

169
00:18:03,680 --> 00:18:06,336
of a proper White House staff.

170
00:18:23,815 --> 00:18:27,085
Is that...Louis Trace?

171
00:18:28,177 --> 00:18:32,308
These decanters are
replicas of metal flasks

172
00:18:32,368 --> 00:18:38,157
that were found on the
battlefield in Jarnac. Correct?

173
00:18:38,522 --> 00:18:40,775
The Italians,
they know their wines,

174
00:18:40,897 --> 00:18:44,287
and the Irish certainly know how to
make a great whiskey.

175
00:18:45,465 --> 00:18:47,740
But I believe the French

176
00:18:47,790 --> 00:18:51,910
have a distinct advantage
when it comes to cognac.

177
00:18:53,878 --> 00:18:55,603
Is that right?

178
00:18:58,324 --> 00:19:01,730
Oh yeah, you'll make
a good house nigga.

179
00:19:04,031 --> 00:19:05,523
Would you care for a demitasse?

180
00:19:05,554 --> 00:19:10,032
"I wish I knew some other way..."

181
00:19:10,303 --> 00:19:13,190
Sometimes it be just me
and Faye up in here.

182
00:19:13,291 --> 00:19:16,313
Me, Faye, and a little
scotch.

183
00:19:24,501 --> 00:19:25,696
Say it, Faye!

184
00:19:25,918 --> 00:19:28,804
What did you do to this potato salad?
- I'll tell you what I did.

185
00:19:28,904 --> 00:19:32,062
I put some dill in it, because
I read in Women's Day,

186
00:19:32,218 --> 00:19:35,711
where pickles drown out the flavor
and dill bring up the flavor.

187
00:19:35,742 --> 00:19:40,562
That's what you tasting right there.
- Oh, okay. Yeah, I like it.

188
00:19:41,107 --> 00:19:43,885
It makes a different, dont' they?
- It really does.

189
00:19:44,359 --> 00:19:48,147
You must be so proud of Cecil.
- You know he got that job by himself.

190
00:19:48,328 --> 00:19:50,404
The White House called him,
he didn't call the White House.

191
00:19:50,485 --> 00:19:52,666
He's a good man.
You got a good man.

192
00:19:52,697 --> 00:19:54,152
She fun man!

193
00:19:54,475 --> 00:19:58,639
Not like this one right here.
Little sourpuss still mad at me.

194
00:19:59,759 --> 00:20:01,681
I got reason.
- No you don't.

195
00:20:01,691 --> 00:20:03,838
I told you I went down to
the number spot.

196
00:20:04,026 --> 00:20:06,461
Played my little numbers,
got me some barbecue,

197
00:20:06,611 --> 00:20:09,143
and I went down. I didn't even
get nothing to drink!

198
00:20:09,244 --> 00:20:13,899
I'm so - I'm so sick of these
number spot stories, Howard.

199
00:20:13,950 --> 00:20:16,875
How you expect me to believe you
was down at the number spot...

200
00:20:16,976 --> 00:20:20,038
Believe or not, it was true.
- Come on, come on, stop this mess.

201
00:20:20,039 --> 00:20:21,765
Come on y'all. Come on...

202
00:20:21,866 --> 00:20:23,436
If you don't believe,
you don't have to believe but...

203
00:20:26,835 --> 00:20:30,470
Stop this mess, right now.
We are here to celebrate.

204
00:20:30,523 --> 00:20:33,834
So y'all could be nice just one time.
- Baby, come on. Get over here.

205
00:20:34,635 --> 00:20:36,131
Celebrate!

206
00:20:36,166 --> 00:20:40,172
That's right. I'll make you happy.
- Y'all need to get a room!

207
00:20:41,169 --> 00:20:43,899
What? - Ain't that the truth!
Or something...

208
00:20:43,999 --> 00:20:46,179
He just drive me crazy!
He just...

209
00:20:47,452 --> 00:20:51,041
You, uh... you wanna
come to the room? - No.

210
00:20:52,842 --> 00:20:55,525
Hey where are the boys at?
- They upstairs playing.

211
00:20:55,586 --> 00:20:59,291
Boys! Get down here!
I need to see your face now!

212
00:20:59,322 --> 00:21:01,619
What y'all doing up there?
- Cecil, congratulations.

213
00:21:01,680 --> 00:21:03,393
Honey, when you gonna take me
to the White House?

214
00:21:03,414 --> 00:21:05,741
You wanna go to the
White House, baby?

215
00:21:06,346 --> 00:21:09,566
You know I wanna go to White
House. - When you want to go?

216
00:21:10,034 --> 00:21:12,630
Don't play with me now,
you know I want to go.

217
00:21:12,651 --> 00:21:14,861
The White House,
that's a big step up.

218
00:21:15,285 --> 00:21:18,980
It is exciting. - Girl, you are
up in that house now!

219
00:21:19,197 --> 00:21:21,237
I want to hear <i>all</i> of the stories.

220
00:21:21,258 --> 00:21:22,737
I don't know how many
stories you gonna hear,

221
00:21:23,155 --> 00:21:24,882
'cus they done swore
him to some kind of

222
00:21:24,982 --> 00:21:27,381
secret code and he
can't tell me nothin'.

223
00:21:27,639 --> 00:21:29,581
No, no, no. Girl,
you give it to him right.

224
00:21:30,419 --> 00:21:32,751
He'll tell you everything!
- That's the key right there.

225
00:21:32,860 --> 00:21:35,173
You listening?
Did you hear her?

226
00:21:35,273 --> 00:21:38,059
Whom do you giving to?
- Crazy. - You got at home.

227
00:21:38,160 --> 00:21:39,300
I can give it to you.

228
00:21:39,301 --> 00:21:41,386
I don't know what are
you talking about. - Elroy!

229
00:21:44,524 --> 00:21:46,524
Here they come.

230
00:21:46,689 --> 00:21:48,829
Boys stop running through this
house, you know better than that.

231
00:21:48,860 --> 00:21:52,233
Elroy, get over here.
Come here.

232
00:21:54,879 --> 00:21:56,517
Give me some money.

233
00:21:58,370 --> 00:22:00,226
Nah... Tell them...

234
00:22:00,297 --> 00:22:02,307
Tell them what you gonna
be when you grow up.

