Gloria looked so happy,
but I didn't feel the same way.

1186
01:47:16,859 --> 01:47:20,871
I guess I wished we were
there for real, instead of show.

1187
01:47:31,203 --> 01:47:33,890
I think that's <i>bon appetite</i>,
everybody.

1188
01:47:33,990 --> 01:47:35,943
You a black motherfu...!

1189
01:47:41,483 --> 01:47:45,272
I want to make myself
clear on this issue.

1190
01:47:47,312 --> 01:47:51,653
If Congress passes sanctions
against South Africa,

1191
01:47:53,620 --> 01:47:58,050
I will be forced to veto
those sanctions.

1192
01:47:58,100 --> 01:48:01,953
Well, Mr. President, we feel
that would be a major mistake.

1193
01:48:02,454 --> 01:48:06,098
The brutal repression of
South African black citizens

1194
01:48:06,119 --> 01:48:09,320
makes no longer
a foreign policy issue,

1195
01:48:09,451 --> 01:48:13,086
but a United States racial issue.

1196
01:48:13,127 --> 01:48:17,367
We're Senators from your own party.
That's why we feel so comfortables

1197
01:48:17,428 --> 01:48:21,204
in letting you know that South
Africa is a human rights disaster.

1198
01:48:21,305 --> 01:48:26,834
Black people are being beaten, tortured,
gunned down in the middle of the street.

1199
01:48:27,059 --> 01:48:31,070
Americans see this on TV.
They're horrified by Apartheid.

1200
01:48:31,111 --> 01:48:34,136
I've made my decision.

1201
01:48:34,337 --> 01:48:38,931
Mr. President, your reputation
as a world leader is at stake.

1202
01:48:39,517 --> 01:48:43,639
The USA needs to be on the right
side of history on the race issue.

1203
01:48:43,994 --> 01:48:46,000
I'll say it again.

1204
01:48:46,458 --> 01:48:49,610
If Congress passes this bill,

1205
01:48:50,769 --> 01:48:52,656
I will veto it.

1206
01:48:53,739 --> 01:48:55,456
Period.

1207
01:49:05,072 --> 01:49:06,796
What, you reading now?

1208
01:49:08,832 --> 01:49:11,557
Get up and do the dishes ‘fore
I shoot you in the head.

1209
01:49:25,036 --> 01:49:28,183
Nothing seemed right to me
after that State Dinner.

1210
01:49:29,001 --> 01:49:30,635
I got all confused.

1211
01:49:58,025 --> 01:50:00,755
They started writing books

1212
01:50:00,924 --> 01:50:05,021
about everything Louis
and his friends had done.

1213
01:50:11,072 --> 01:50:13,679
Louis was never a criminal.

1214
01:50:17,180 --> 01:50:19,357
He was a hero!

1215
01:50:19,858 --> 01:50:23,093
Fighting to save the soul
of our country.

1216
01:50:34,760 --> 01:50:36,935
Would you like a cookie?

1217
01:50:40,350 --> 01:50:43,336
Cookie? - Thank you.
- Thank you.

1218
01:50:45,013 --> 01:50:46,253
Cookie?

1219
01:51:01,242 --> 01:51:03,832
I had always loved serving.

1220
01:51:04,468 --> 01:51:06,884
But it just felt different now.

1221
01:51:09,839 --> 01:51:14,108
I didn't know that an old man
could feel so lost.

1222
01:51:15,321 --> 01:51:17,683
But that's how I felt...

1223
01:51:18,491 --> 01:51:20,524
That's how I felt.

1224
01:51:27,255 --> 01:51:30,390
Americans always turned a blind eye

1225
01:51:30,702 --> 01:51:33,525
to what we had done to our own.

1226
01:51:34,009 --> 01:51:37,620
We look out to the world and judge.

1227
01:51:38,422 --> 01:51:41,532
We hear about the
concentration camps.

1228
01:51:42,137 --> 01:51:46,602
But these camps went on
for 200 years...

1229
01:51:46,902 --> 01:51:48,850
Right here, in America.

1230
01:52:01,813 --> 01:52:04,536
I buried my daddy right over there.

1231
01:52:07,906 --> 01:52:11,442
My mamma would have
been right proud of me,

1232
01:52:12,207 --> 01:52:14,400
being with a man like yous.

1233
01:52:14,909 --> 01:52:18,448
Taking such good care of me
all of these years.

1234
01:52:21,288 --> 01:52:24,124
I love you, Cecil Gaines.

1235
01:52:25,728 --> 01:52:28,537
I love you more, Gloria.

1236
01:52:41,007 --> 01:52:43,588
Are you sure about this?

1237
01:52:44,313 --> 01:52:46,169
Yes, sir.

1238
01:52:46,802 --> 01:52:49,950
I just want to be the one who
tell you first, that's all.

1239
01:52:51,391 --> 01:52:56,226
You're the best butler here.
You are like family, Cecil.

1240
01:52:58,622 --> 01:53:00,598
It's been an honor serving you.

1241
01:53:02,370 --> 01:53:05,421
Not just for me, I'm sure I speak
for all the Presidents

1242
01:53:05,492 --> 01:53:09,859
when I say that you've served
your country well.

1243
01:53:12,174 --> 01:53:13,916
Thank you, Mr. President.

1244
01:53:18,698 --> 01:53:20,052
Cecil?

1245
01:53:22,203 --> 01:53:25,039
This whole civil rights issue...

1246
01:53:28,928 --> 01:53:31,648
I sometimes fear I'm...

1247
01:53:32,350 --> 01:53:36,758
...on the wrong side of it.
That I'm...just wrong.

1248
01:53:39,104 --> 01:53:42,782
Sometimes I think I'm just
scared of what it really means.

1249
01:53:43,647 --> 01:53:46,833
But I'm trying to not be
so scared anymore.

1250
01:53:48,086 --> 01:53:50,682
Who do we want to free?
- Mandela!

1251
01:53:50,723 --> 01:53:52,871
When do we want him free?
- Now!

1252
01:53:52,972 --> 01:53:57,470
Twenty years ago, we marched in
this country for our rights.

1253
01:53:59,433 --> 01:54:03,835
Today, we march to free
the people of South Africa.

1254
01:54:05,362 --> 01:54:09,954
Ronald Reagan has attacked or dismantled
every civil rights program

1255
01:54:10,908 --> 01:54:12,710
that has ever been put in to place!

1256
01:54:13,627 --> 01:54:17,423
Aiding the oppression of black South
Africans is absolutely consistent

1257
01:54:17,494 --> 01:54:21,177
with his policies on
race issues. Am I right?

1258
01:54:21,228 --> 01:54:23,593
Am I right?

1259
01:54:29,635 --> 01:54:31,488
Excuse me...Steven!
Where is Steven?

1260
01:54:32,106 --> 01:54:34,040
Free Mandela y'all!

1261
01:54:53,083 --> 01:54:55,028
Hi, dad.

1262
01:54:56,338 --> 01:54:58,301
Hi, Louis.

1263
01:54:59,895 --> 01:55:02,011
What are you doing here?

1264
01:55:08,349 --> 01:55:10,645
I'm here to protest with you.

1265
01:55:13,807 --> 01:55:16,496
You'll get arrested dad. You'll
lose your job.

1266
01:55:18,975 --> 01:55:21,327
I've lost you.

1267
01:55:25,195 --> 01:55:27,163
I'm sorry...

1268
01:55:37,164 --> 01:55:39,497
I'm sorry, son...

1269
01:55:59,086 --> 01:56:02,488
Don't worry dad, we'll be
out of here in a few hours.

1270
01:56:03,173 --> 01:56:05,364
Who said I was worried?

1271
01:56:10,127 --> 01:56:13,994
After going to jail, I thought
I had seen it all.

1272
01:56:18,823 --> 01:56:20,450
But I'd never imagined

1273
01:56:20,491 --> 01:56:26,164
I'd see a black man be
a real contender

1274
01:56:26,265 --> 01:56:29,727
for the President of the US.

1275
01:56:52,369 --> 01:56:56,629
Gloria and I would walk to our
polling place every night

1276
01:56:56,690 --> 01:57:01,246
to see where we would be
voting for Barack Obama.

1277
01:57:02,590 --> 01:57:06,738
We would just stare at it
and smile.

1278
01:57:12,786 --> 01:57:15,490
You done?
- Pretty much.

1279
01:57:15,551 --> 01:57:17,736
Good. You done good.

1280
01:57:19,692 --> 01:57:23,284
You done pretty good
there. Thanks, honey.

1281
01:57:25,485 --> 01:57:28,594
How come Louis' wife
name that child...

1282
01:57:29,472 --> 01:57:32,707
Shaquanda? - Now don't
start that again.

1283
01:57:32,768 --> 01:57:36,720
I ain't starting it, I just don't
know what kind of name that is.

1284
01:57:36,921 --> 01:57:40,173
I mean, really, Shaquanda?!

1285
01:57:40,760 --> 01:57:43,443
I think she done that
just to spite me.

1286
